issue.title: Using Java library with DNNL

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Describe the bug**
I've compiled java jar with options:
`./build.sh --use_dnnl --use_openmp  --build_java --parallel --config RelWithDebInfo`

At the end, I've used `onnxruntime4j-1.1.0-with-binaries.jar` in my java application; but after trying some of the benchmarks and analyzing model exec with profiler I've noticed that DNNL is not in the call stack and MLAS is used instead;

I've found an option:
```
var opts = new OrtSession.SessionOptions()
opts.addDnnl(true);
```

which gives me an error: 
```
ai.onnxruntime.OrtException: Error code - ORT_INVALID_ARGUMENT - message: This binary was not compiled with DNNL support.
	at ai.onnxruntime.OrtSession$SessionOptions.addDnnl(Native Method)
```

Is this the way of turning DNNL in java env or I'm doing something wrong?

**Urgency**
Actually this blocks an integration of ONNX runtime into one of our production services;

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): macOS
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): source
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.1.0
- Python version: 3.7
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): n/a
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): clang Apple LLVM version 10.0.1 (clang-1001.0.46.4)
- CUDA/cuDNN version: n/a
- GPU model and memory: n/a

**To Reproduce**
see above

issue.title: [Java] Adds extra providers

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**:
Adds hooks for using ArmNN, CoreML and ROCM to the Java API.

Also adds an OrtFlags mechanism for aggregating bitset enums on the Java side, and updates the NNAPI call to use them (along with the new CoreML one).

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve? C API <-> Java API parity.

Depends on #6765 as it includes the flag added there.

There are other updates necessary to get the Java API back to parity in terms of the providers, but I'm waiting on responses to #6553 and #6676 before I can make progress.

issue.title: Dynamic GPU support

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
I am using the library on various systems which might have GPU and/or the necessary CUDA libraries installed. So I would like to have a possibility let onnxruntime decide which device to use.

As soon as I ship onnxruntime with GPU support (taken from Maven) on systems where GPU is not available or not installed CUDA wise onnxruntime fails to start.

**System information**
1.7.0

**Describe the solution you'd like**
Onnxruntime should have following behavior:
1. Check to load GPU libraries
2. Check to have GPU device available
3. Fallback to CPU if 1 or 2 failed

issue.title: Fix the warnings found by VC++ static code analyzer and add it to the CPU CI build

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: 
1. Fix the warnings found by VC++ static code analyzer and add it to the CPU CI build
2. Update pybind11 to a newer version because it contains a warning fix from me.
3. Remove the cancel function of the Eigen thread pool. It is not used anywhere, and we don't know if it ever works.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?

Before this change, we even didn't test any EPs(other than CPU) in the java code. 

- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.

body: @Craigacp Do my upcoming shared cuda provider changes help resolve some of this? Or is there still an issue with 'delete on exit' with the shared libraries too?

Well it'll make everything load properly. Windows' behaviour with `deleteOnExit` is a pain for Java code which unpacks dlls at runtime, but there isn't much to be done about it unless we have direct control of the unloading code. I'll need to make equivalent modifications to the Java loader for the other libraries that have shared providers, and I'm still a little worried about the way it loads things inside the native code because it's not clear to me that it's pulling things in from the right path, but if it's working then presumably the platform dynamic loader is figuring it out.

Did you test the Java/CUDA bits on both Windows & Linux? I guess I'll need to test DNNL on macOS as well, as that could also have different behaviour.

@Craigacp I ran through all of our pipeline tests, and I thought that includes Java on windows & linux.

As for the path it looks for the shared providers, on Windows it looks for them in the same path as onnxruntime.dll is. On Linux it does a similar thing through RPATH (search for -rpath in onnxruntime_providers.cmake for where it's set). So this should always work (done this way for security and simplicity)

issue.title: [Java] Adds support for DNNL, OpenVINO, TensorRT shared providers and refactors the CUDA shared provider loader

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**:

Refactors the native library loading in Java to allow CUDA to be loaded on demand, fixing #7044. Then expands the shared provider library loading to DNNL, OpenVINO, TensorRT, fixing #6553.

Added a flag to the native library loading to allow users to supply a directory which contains all the native libraries, fixing #8003. This is also the only way to make the shared library providers load from a different place than the jar, as the individual library path specification conflicts with the way that the ONNX Runtime native code loads the shared library providers.

I also slightly refactored the Java cmake bits, and added the `--console=plain` flag to the gradle executions to stop gradle writing over cmake's output.

**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve? Re-enables DNNL, OpenVINO and TensorRT in Java by allowing them to be packaged in the jar and dynamically loaded in the same way CUDA is.
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. Fixes #6553. Fixes #7044. Fixes #8003.

issue.title: Fix Android java API failure

repository.name: onnxruntime
repository.description: ONNX Runtime: cross-platform, high performance ML inferencing and training accelerator

issue.body:
**Description**: Fix Android AAR package java failure

**Motivation and Context**
- The change of adding support of SharedProviders (#8013) added some code which will fail on Android since we do not extract the library to a temp folder, and there is no shared provider on Android
- Even the e2e test fails, the Android CI pipeline will still pass, the error was undetected for a while
- Modify the test to use Gradle connectedAndroidTest, which will fail the pipeline, see https://aiinfra.visualstudio.com/Lotus/_build/results?buildId=171772&view=logs&j=05890eb8-2c35-5d5f-6c21-ffaec9f22ea9&t=507a309f-2199-517f-4e2a-f9425056f40a
- Add E2E package test in the packaging pipeline
- Move Android packaging pipeline from GPU pipeline to CPU pipeline 
- Failed run on 2nd commit of this PR (without java fix) https://dev.azure.com/onnxruntime/onnxruntime/_build/results?buildId=480725&view=logs&j=5bc85223-5fed-55e3-d6db-7543b894f171&t=18079af2-fcf0-521f-fa55-ed80f159d401
